message: >-
  If you use these patterns in your systems, research, or publications,
  please cite this repository using the metadata below.
type: software
title: >-
  banking-agent-audit: Governance Patterns for Autonomous AI Agents
  in Regulated Banking
authors:
  - family-names: Bhaduri
    given-names: Kunjar
    affiliation: North Texas Capital Investments
    website: "https://linkedin.com/in/kunjarbhaduri"
repository-code: "https://github.com/linus10x/banking-agent-audit"
url: "https://github.com/linus10x/banking-agent-audit"
abstract: >-
  Reference governance patterns, schemas, and runnable implementations for
  audit-ready autonomous AI agents in regulated banking. Ships five corrected
  governance primitives — an autonomy-level promotion gate (A0 through A4) that
  refuses promotion on unmet lower-rung controls and requires independent
  attestation of its inputs; a fail-closed sovereign-veto kill switch whose
  clearance requires an authenticated non-agent principal and which an agent
  cannot self-clear; a tamper-evident hash-chain ledger whose verifier branches
  the genesis seed so deployer-keyed and legacy chains both verify, with
  end-to-end regeneration detected via a non-optional production-mode witness
  anchor; a DEFCON risk-state machine with a transition-direction guard that
  forbids one-call de-escalation from HALT; and an effective-challenge harness
  that rejects self-challenge in code and records an operator independence
  attestation. On top of the primitives it implements two tested banking
  controls — model-risk validation gated on attested challenger independence,
  and an ECOA/Regulation B section 1002.9 adverse-action gate with the FCRA
  section 615 overlay — plus a sanctions/AML disposition-workflow pattern that
  bundles no sanctions list and screens against a pluggable, deployer-wired list
  provider. Sub-verticals for mortgage (HMDA/Regulation C, the interagency AVM
  quality-control standards), consumer credit (Truth in Lending/Regulation Z),
  and deposit/payments fraud (Regulation E) ship as documented patterns with
  primary-source citations. The test suite includes property-based fuzzing, five
  committed adversarial primitive probes, a golden corpus of real public
  banking enforcement actions, and a mutation pass over the security predicates.
  Maps to primary banking regulatory anchors including the Bank Secrecy Act
  (31 U.S.C. 5311 et seq.), ECOA/Regulation B (12 CFR 1002.9), the Fair Credit
  Reporting Act (15 U.S.C. 1681m), the Home Mortgage Disclosure Act
  (Regulation C), the Truth in Lending Act (Regulation Z), Regulation E, the
  interagency Automated Valuation Model quality-control rule, and the 2026
  revised interagency Model Risk Management guidance (OCC Bulletin 2026-13,
  superseding SR 11-7). This is reference IP for adoption, not a control
  operating in production; the sanctions surface ships no list.
keywords:
  - AI governance
  - autonomous agents
  - banking
  - model risk management
  - fair lending
  - adverse action
  - BSA/AML
  - audit trail
  - human-in-the-loop
  - compliance
